# AI prompting

## Prompting rules and principles
[Read in detail](./prompting/prompting_rules_and_principles.md)

**tl;dr**: despite *understanding* natural language, AI is a software. It needs concise input to provide proper output. 

These prompting practices are fundamental to how all instruction-tuned LLMs interpret input:

| Principle                                              | Applies to All Models | Reason                                                   |
| ------------------------------------------------------ | --------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| Clear **role → task → constraints → format** structure | ✅                     | All models rely on context–instruction parsing           |
| Using **Markdown headings**                            | ✅                     | Markdown is tokenized cleanly by all models              |
| Including **examples (“few-shot prompting”)**          | ✅                     | Demonstrations improve in-context learning universally   |
| **Explicit output formats** (e.g., JSON, code fences)  | ✅                     | Models align strongly with delimited outputs             |
| **Constraints** (“don’t do X”)                         | ✅                     | All instruction-following models weigh negative examples |
| **Iterative refinement**                               | ✅                     | Output-feedback loops work for any conversational LLM    |


## Prompting across models
[Read in detail](./prompting/prompt_adaptation_across_models.md)

**tl;dr**: Understand prompts depends on what LLM was taught to understand. Each LLM needs a specific tweaks in prompting for optimal results.

| Feature                                 | GPT Family | Claude | Copilot      | Gemini |
| --------------------------------------- | ---------- | ------ | ------------ | ------ |
| Understands headings                    | ✅          | ✅      | ⚠️ (limited) | ✅      |
| Handles nested Markdown (`json` inside) | ✅          | ✅      | ⚠️           | ✅      |
| Follows JSON schema strictly            | ✅          | ✅      | ⚠️           | ⚠️     |
| Long context (100k+ tokens)             | ✅          | ✅✅     | ❌            | ✅      |
| Handles multi-step logical reasoning    | ✅✅         | ✅      | ⚠️           | ✅      |

## Can I use the settings instead of accurate prompts?

**tl;dr: NO**

| Strategy                    | Can it be done in settings? | Should it be per prompt?     |
| --------------------------- | --------------------------- | ---------------------------- |
| Use specific docs/resources | ❌ Not in settings           | ✅ Yes, include in prompt     |
| Version-specific context    | ❌ Not in settings           | ✅ Yes, include in prompt     |
| Cite sources / confidence   | ❌ Not in settings           | ✅ Yes, per prompt            |
| Live verification           | ✅ If browsing/RAG enabled   | ✅ Per prompt, specify source |

On top of that, additional resources must be added, otherwise LLM knows what is was taught and will just pretend to open your link :)

# Lingo

## MCP

## Open-source standard for connecting AI applications to external systems.

![][image1]

## Agent

[LLM-powered](https://www.dataiku.com/stories/detail/ai-agents/?utm_campaign=agentic%20AI&utm_source=emea-adwords&utm_medium=paid-search&utm_content=awareness&gad_source=1&gad_campaignid=22355533428) system designed to achieve objective autonomously, making decisions and taking actions on its own, within set boundaries.

### Agent frameworks

[Frameworks](https://blog.dataiku.com/open-source-frameworks-for-llm-powered-agents) to implement and scale agent systems, complex logic, integrations with multiple APIs and LLMs.

## LLM

###### *Large language models (LLMs) are a category of [deep learning](https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/deep-learning) models trained on immense amounts of data, making them capable of understanding and generating natural language and other types of content to perform a wide range of tasks. LLMs are built on a type of [neural network](https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/neural-networks) architecture called a [transformer](https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/transformer-model) which excels at handling sequences of words and capturing patterns in text.* (“What Are Large Language Models (LLMs)?”)

“What Are Large Language Models (LLMs)?” *IBM*, https://www.ibm.com/think/topics/large-language-models. Accessed 9 October 2025

## AI Application

Just a software that uses AI
